&lt;h2 id=&#34;Step-8-install-phpMyAdmin-so-you-can-easily-manage-your-MySQL-databases-via-a-nice-frontend-written-in-PHP&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Step-8-install-phpMyAdmin-so-you-can-easily-manage-your-MySQL-databases-via-a-nice-frontend-written-in-PHP&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Step 8, install phpMyAdmin so you can easily manage your MySQL databases via a nice frontend written in PHP.&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Step 8, install phpMyAdmin so you can easily manage your MySQL databases via a nice frontend written in PHP.&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt; phpMyAdmin is NOT available as a package in the official Cent-OS repositories. Important: before continue the following step, go &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.phpmyadmin.net/home/_page/downloads.php&#34;&gt;http://www.phpmyadmin.net/home\_page/downloads.php&lt;/a&gt; and check what is the latest version available. (At the time of writing this article the latest version of phpMyAdmin is 4.2.5. You can replace the version number in the following command.)&lt;/p&gt;
